# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hms-warrior-1860
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The **68-pounder cannon** was an artillery piece designed and used by the British Armed Forces in the mid-19th century.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon was a smoothbore muzzle-loading gun manufactured in several weights firing projectiles of 68 lb (31 kg).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Colonel William Dundas designed the 112 cwt version in 1841 which was cast the following year.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The most common variant, weighing 95 long cwt (4,800 kg), dates from 1846.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] It entered service with the Royal Artillery and the Royal Navy and saw active service with both arms during the Crimean War.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Over 2,000 were made and it gained a reputation as the finest smoothbore cannon ever made.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The gun was produced at a time when new rifled and breech loading guns were beginning to make their mark on artillery.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] At first the 68-pounder's reliability and power meant that it was retained even on new warships such as HMS *Warrior*, but eventually new rifled muzzle loaders made all smoothbore muzzle-loading guns obsolete.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] However, the large surplus stocks of 68-pounders were given new life when converted to take rifled projectiles; the cannon remained in service and was not declared obsolete until 1921.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon was designed in response to the need for heavier weaponry as armour on ships of the line improved.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Colonel William Dundas, the government's Inspector of Artillery between 1839 and 1852, designed the cannon in 1846.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] It was cast by the Low Moor Iron Works in Bradford in 1847 and entered service soon after.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Like numerous cannon before it, it was a cast iron smoothbore loaded from the muzzle.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon was relatively cheap to produce – the Royal Commission on the Defence of the United Kingdom estimated that each cannon cost approximately £167.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Over 2000 were cast before 1861 and its exceptional durability, range and accuracy earned it a reputation as the finest smoothbore cannon ever made.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The gun was a traditional muzzleloader; it needed to be loaded from the front end of the barrel.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Before it could be loaded the bore of the barrel was cleaned with a sponge, after which a propellant charge (gunpowder in a cloth bag) was rammed down into the breech.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] This was followed by a projectile, often encased in wadding.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The gun was primed (using a metal spike inserted through the vent that pierced the charge), and fired using a percussion cap (which ignited the charge and forced the projectile out of the barrel).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The estimated rate of fire of this weapon was between 55 and 70 seconds, though loading speed could be expected to fall off as crew became fatigued.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The 68-pounder had an effective range of approximately 3,000 yd (2,700 m), however at its maximum elevation of 15 degrees it had a maximum range of 3,620 yd (3,310 m), a distance that the projectile would cover in 15 seconds.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] With a 16 lb (7.3 kg) powder charge (the "far" charge, although the gun was proofed to 25 lb charges) the cannon fired a 68 lb (31 kg) solid shot at a muzzle velocity of 1,579 ft/s (481 m/s).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon could fire solid shot, explosive shells, grapeshot, case shot and "Martins Liquid Iron Shell" (thin walled shells filled with molten iron, intended to serve as heated shot).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Although the cannon's barrel bore was 8.12 inches (20.6 cm), both shot and shells were 7.92 inches (20.1 cm) in diameter.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] This allowed a windage gap of 0.1 in (0.25 cm) around the projectile; enough to aid the loading process, but not enough to seriously diffuse the propellant gasses.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The official weight of the shot was listed at 68 lbs but in reality this varied according to the material of the shot itself; cast iron shot weighed 67 lb (30 kg), wrought iron shot and steel shot weighed 72 lb (33 kg), and chilled steel weighed 68 lb 8 oz (31.1 kg).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] It was estimated that one 68-pound shot had the destructive power equivalent to five 32-pound shot.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The explosive shells were primed with 4 lb (1.8 kg) of gunpowder.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] They were fitted with simple fuses that were ignited by the flash of the charge – early wooden fuses were eventually replaced by more reliable fuses designed by Captain Edward Boxer in 1849.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The gun crew still had to gauge the best length of fuse for the range they were firing – ideally the shell should explode just before hitting its target.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] To prevent the shell exploding in the barrel it was fitted with a sabot to ensure the fuse faced away from the charge.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] On land a minimum crew of nine men (usually commanded by a non-commissioned officer) was required to fire the gun, which was normally mounted on a traversing gun carriage.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] On board a ship the gun crew could be doubled to 18 men who needed to traverse the gun carriage by hand, using hand spikes and rope tackles.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The extra crew was because sailing ships usually only fired their cannon from one side of the deck.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] In the unlikely event of both sides being in action at once, nine men would be detached to man the gun opposite.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] In both cases the gun was elevated using wooden wedges driven under the breech of the barrel by brute force.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] It was aimed using an advanced hexagonal sighting mechanism marked with the elevation on one face and the gun's range (according to different weights of cartridge charges) on the other five faces.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon was put to use both on land and at sea.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] It was fitted to numerous Royal Navy warships of different sizes such as HMS *Queen*, *Odin*, *Victor Emmanuel*, *Sepoy* and the *Conqueror*-class ships of the line.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Several of these ships saw action during the Crimean War where the 68-pounder was used extensively during the Siege of Sevastopol.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Along with 32-pounders and Lancaster guns they were taken from their ship mountings and dragged up to siege batteries by the Naval Brigade, from where they regularly bombarded Russian positions for the next year.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The cannon was also fitted in large numbers to the *Aetna*-class ironclad floating batteries, although these had little impact on the war.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Most notably the 68-pounder was fitted to the *Warrior*-class ironclads *Warrior* and *Black Prince*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Originally it was intended to fit forty 68-pounders, primarily on one gun deck, but this specification changed during their building and they were finally equipped with twenty-six 68-pounders (13 on each side).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Alongside these, the ships were equipped with new rifled breech loading Armstrong guns of two types; 7 inch and 40 pounders.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Although the Armstrong guns represented a new direction in artillery, the breech loading mechanism meant that they were unable to withstand the explosion of a heavy cartridge.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Smaller cartridge charges were therefore required and the gun's muzzle velocity suffered as a result.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Ironically the Armstrong Guns were therefore incapable of penetrating the armour fitted to the *Warrior*-class ships, while the 68-pounder (with its high muzzle velocity) could.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] As late as 1867 it was planned to fit the new *Plover*-class gunvessels with 68-pounders, but they were instead completed with a RML 7 inch gun and a RML 64 pounder 64 cwt gun.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] On land the 68-pounder was used extensively in British coastal defences constructed during the 1850s - notably at forts like Gomer and Elson defending Portsmouth, and Forts Victoria, Albert and Freshwater Redoubt defending the Needles Passage.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The 1859 Royal Commission envisaged arming the numerous new forts they proposed with the 68-pounder cannon and costed for them accordingly.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The introduction of the Armstrong gun initially led many to think that weapon would be used instead, but whilst the forts were being built, the Armstrong gun's weaknesses were exposed and the military reverted to using muzzle loaded weapons.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] However, the advantages of rifling and the Armstrong's wrought iron construction were retained, leading to a new design of artillery piece – rifled muzzle loaders.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] The introduction of rifled muzzle loaders (also classed as RMLs) rendered smoothbore guns largely obsolete.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] However, the 68-pounder and other smoothbores still existed in large numbers and various attempts were made to adapt the guns to fire new projectiles.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Eventually Captain William Palliser patented a method of boring out the gun barrel and inserting a wrought iron rifled liner.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] This allowed rifled shot and shells to be fired from old smoothbore cannon and experiments revealed that it made them even more powerful than they had been before.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] Introduced in 1872, 68-pounders adapted in this way had a calibre of 6.29 inches (16.0 cm) and were known as a **RML 68-pounder**, or officially as the **RML 80-pounder 5 ton**.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] With a 10 lb (4.5 kg) powder charge they could fire an 80 lb (36 kg) projectile at a muzzle velocity of 1,240 feet per second (380 m/s).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] They were deployed as coast defence and garrison artillery around the British Empire and remained in service until eventually declared obsolete in 1921.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/68-pounder-gun] At least two 68 pounders were converted to 7 in (18 cm) 6.55 long tons (6.66 t; 7.34 short tons) RML guns, firing a 115 lb (52 kg) or 150 lb (68 kg) double shot.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz's reign began during the Ottoman Empire's resurgence following the Crimean War and two decades of the Tanzimat reforms, though it was now reliant on European capital.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He was the first Ottoman sultan who traveled to Western Europe in a diplomatic capacity, visiting a number of important European capitals including Paris, London, and Vienna in the summer of 1867.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The decade after his ascension was dominated by the duo of Fuad Pasha and Aali Pasha, who accelerated reorganization of the Empire.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The Vilayet Law was promulgated, Western codes were applied to more aspects of Ottoman law, and the millets were restructured.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The issue of Tanzimat dualism continued to plague the empire, however.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The first semblance of an opposition party coalesced around detractors of Fuad and Aali, the Young Ottomans.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Once they were dead by 1871, Abdul Aziz promulgated reactionary ministries and attempted personal rule, revealing his eccentricities.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His autocracy became the target of the Young Ottomans, leading to demands for a constitution.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In his last years as sultan, famine, economic crisis and default, diplomatic isolation, government dysfunction, and uprisings by Christian minorities culminated into a general international crisis known as the Great Eastern Crisis.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz was deposed on 30 May 1876 by his ministers on the grounds of having mismanaged the economy, and was found dead from suicide six days later.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz was born at Eyüp Palace, Constantinople (Istanbul) on 8 February 1830.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His parents were Mahmud II and Pertevniyal Sultan, originally named Besime, a Circassian.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The Pertevniyal Valide Sultan Mosque was built under the patronage of his mother.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The construction work began in November 1869 and the mosque was finished in 1871.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His paternal grandparents were Sultan Abdul Hamid I and Sultana Nakşidil Sultan.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Several accounts identify his paternal grandmother with Aimée du Buc de Rivéry, a cousin of Empress Joséphine.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Pertevniyal was a sister of Hushiyar Qadin, third wife of Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Hushiyar and Ibrahim were the parents of Isma'il Pasha.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz received an Ottoman education but was nevertheless an ardent admirer of the material progress that was being achieved in the West.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He was the first Ottoman sultan who traveled to Western Europe, visiting a number of important European capitals including Paris, London, and Vienna in the summer of 1867.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In addition to his interest in literature, Abdulaziz was also a classical music composer.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He took a special interest in documenting the Ottoman Empire.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Some of his compositions, together with those of the other members of the Ottoman dynasty, have been collected in the album *European Music at the Ottoman Court* by the London Academy of Ottoman Court Music.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Between 1861 and 1871, the Tanzimat reforms which began during the reign of his brother Abdulmejid I were continued under the leadership of his chief ministers, Mehmed Fuad Pasha and Mehmed Emin Aali Pasha.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] New administrative districts (*vilayets*) were set up in 1864 and a Council of State was established in 1868.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Public education was organized on the French model and Istanbul University was reorganised as a modern institution in 1861.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He was also integral in establishing the first Ottoman civil code, the *Mecelle*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Under his reign, Turkey's first postage stamps were issued in 1863, and the Ottoman Empire joined the Universal Postal Union in 1875 as a founding member.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz cultivated good relations with France and the United Kingdom.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1867 he was the first Ottoman sultan to visit Western Europe.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Ostensibly he was to see the Paris exhibition of 1867 at Napoleon III's invitation, however the real goal was to reestablish Ottoman credit and forestall a Franco-Russian intervention in rebellious Crete.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His voyage in visiting order (from 21 June 1867 to 7 August 1867): Istanbul – Messina – Naples – Toulon – Marseille – Paris – Boulogne – Dover – London – Dover – Calais – Brussels – Koblenz – Vienna – Budapest – Orșova – Vidin – Ruse – Varna – Istanbul.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In London, he was made a Knight of the Garter by Queen Victoria and shown a Royal Navy Fleet Review with Ismail Pasha.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He travelled by a private rail car, which today can be found in the Rahmi M.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Impressed by the museums in Paris (30 June – 10 July 1867), London (12–23 July 1867) and Vienna (28–30 July 1867) he ordered the establishment of an Imperial Museum in Istanbul: the Istanbul Archaeology Museum.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1868, Abdulaziz received visits from Eugénie de Montijo, Empress consort of Napoleon III of France and other foreign monarchs on their way to the opening of the Suez Canal.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He took Eugénie to see his mother in Dolmabahçe Palace.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] However, his mother Pertevniyal Sultan considered the presence of a foreign woman within her private quarters of the seraglio to be an insult.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] She reportedly slapped Eugénie across the face, which almost caused an international incident.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] According to another account, Pertevniyal was outraged by the forwardness of Eugénie in taking the arm of one of her sons while he gave a tour of the palace garden, and she gave the Empress a slap on the stomach as a possibly more subtly intended reminder that they were not in France.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The first Ottoman railroads were opened between İzmir–Aydın and Alexandria–Cairo in 1856, during the reign of Sultan Abdulmejid I.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The first large railway terminal within present-day Turkey, the Alsancak Terminal in İzmir, was opened in 1858.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] However, these were individual, unconnected railroads, without a railway network.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Sultan Abdulaziz established the first Ottoman railway networks.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] On 17 April 1869, the concession for the Rumelia Railway (i.e.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Balkan Railways, *Rumeli* (Rumelia) meaning the Balkan peninsula in Ottoman Turkish) which connected Istanbul to Vienna was awarded to Baron Maurice de Hirsch (Moritz Freiherr Hirsch auf Gereuth), a Bavaria-born banker from Belgium.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The project foresaw a railway route from Istanbul via Edirne, Plovdiv and Sarajevo to the shore of the Sava River.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1873, the first Sirkeci Terminal in Istanbul was opened.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The temporary Sirkeci terminal building was later replaced with the current one which was built between 1888 and 1890 (during the reign of Abdülhamid II) and became the final destination terminus of the Orient Express.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1871, Sultan Abdulaziz established the Anatolia Railway.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Construction works of the 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge on the Asian side of Istanbul, from Haydarpaşa to Pendik, began in 1871.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The line was opened on 22 September 1872.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The railway was extended to Gebze, which opened on 1 January 1873.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In August 1873 the railway reached Izmit.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Another railway extension was built in 1871 to serve a populated area along Bursa and the Sea of Marmara.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The Anatolia Railway was then extended to Ankara and eventually to Mesopotamia, Syria and Arabia during the reign of Sultan Abdulhamid II, with the completion of the Baghdad Railway and Hejaz Railway.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Also in 1867, Abdulaziz became the first Ottoman Sultan to formally recognize the title of Khedive (Viceroy) to be used by the Governor of the Ottoman Eyalet of Egypt and Sudan (1517–1867), which thus became the autonomous Ottoman Khedivate of Egypt and Sudan (1867–1914).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Muhammad Ali Pasha and his descendants had been the governors of Ottoman Egypt and Sudan since 1805, but were willing to use the higher title of Khedive, which was unrecognized by the Ottoman government until 1867.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In return, the first Khedive, Ismail Pasha, had agreed a year earlier (in 1866) to increase the annual tax revenues which Egypt and Sudan would provide for the Ottoman treasury.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Between 1854 and 1894, the revenues from Egypt and Sudan were often declared as a surety by the Ottoman government for borrowing loans from British and French banks.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz gave special emphasis on modernizing the Ottoman Navy.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1875, the Ottoman Navy had 21 battleships and 173 warships of other types, ranking as the third largest navy in the world after the British and French navies.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His passion for the Navy, ships and sea can be observed in the wall paintings and pictures of the Beylerbeyi Palace, which was constructed during his reign.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The subsequent decision to increase agricultural taxes for paying the Ottoman public debt to foreign creditors (mainly British and French banks) triggered the Great Eastern Crisis in the empire's Balkan provinces.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The crisis culminated in the Russo-Turkish War (1877–78) that devastated the already struggling Ottoman economy, which led to the establishment of the Ottoman Public Debt Administration in 1881, during the early years of Sultan Abdulhamid II's reign.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The global financial turmoil increased the importance for Britain of the sureties regarding the Ottoman tax revenues from Egypt and Sudan for the repayment of Ottoman debts to British banks.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Combined with the strategically important Suez Canal which was opened in 1869, these sureties were influential in the British government's decision to occupy Egypt and Sudan in 1882, with the pretext of helping the Ottoman-Egyptian government to put down the ʻUrabi revolt (1879–1882).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] By 1871, both Fuad Pasha and Aali Pasha were dead.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The Second French Empire, the Western European model embraced by Sultan Abdulaziz, had been defeated in the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz turned to the Russian Empire for friendship as unrest in the Balkan provinces continued.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He increasingly relied on Mahmud Nedim Pasha, an incompetent statesman known as "Nedimoff" in the press for his Russophilia.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1875, the Herzegovinian rebellion triggered further unrest in the Balkan provinces, beginning a general diplomatic crisis known as the Great Eastern Crisis.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In 1876, the April Uprising saw insurrection spreading among the Bulgarians.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Ill feeling mounted against Russia for its encouragement of the rebellions.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] While no single event led to his deposition, the crop failure of 1873 and his lavish expenditures on the Ottoman Navy and on new palaces which he had built, along with mounting public debt, helped to create an atmosphere that conducted to the end of his reign.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz was deposed by his ministers on 30 May 1876.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] A constitutional committee headed by Midhat Pasha ran the country after his death, elevating his half-brother Murad V to the throne.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] However Murad V's mental health quickly deteriorated, resulting in another deposition after a 90-day reign.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdul Hamid II was brought to the throne, and Turkey soon found itself at war with Russia without its traditional allies.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Following Sultan Abdulaziz's dethronement, he was taken into a room at the Topkapı Palace, which happened to be the same room that Sultan Selim III was murdered in.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] The room caused him to be concerned for his life and he subsequently requested to be moved to Beylerbeyi Palace.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His request was denied for the palace was considered inconvenient for his situation and he was moved to Feriye Palace instead.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] He nevertheless had grown increasingly nervous and paranoid about his security.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In the morning of 4 June, Abdulaziz asked for a pair of scissors to trim his beard.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Shortly after this, he was found dead in a pool of blood flowing from two wounds in his arms.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Several physicians were allowed to examine his body.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Sotto, Physician attached to the Imperial and Royal Embassy of Austria-Hungary; Dr.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Spagnolo, Marc Markel, Jatropoulo, Abdinour, Servet, J. de Castro, A.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Dickson, Physician of the British Embassy; Dr.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Vitalis, Physician of the Sanitary Board; Dr.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] One of those physicians also stated that "His skin was very pale, and entirely free from bruises, marks or spots of any kind whatever.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] There was no lividity of the lips indicating suffocation nor any sign of pressure having been applied to the throat".
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz's death was documented as a suicide.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] There are several sources claiming the death of Abdulaziz was due to an assassination.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Islamic nationalist author Necip Fazıl Kısakürek claimed that it was a clandestine operation carried out by the British.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Another similar claim is based on the book *The Memoirs of Sultan Abdulhamid II*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In the book, which turned out to be a fraud, the author claims that Sultan Murad V had begun to show signs of paranoia, madness, and continuous fainting and vomiting until the day of his coronation, and he even threw himself into a pool yelling at his guards to protect his life.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] High-ranking politicians of the time were afraid the public would become outraged and revolt to bring Abdulaziz back to power.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Thus, they arranged the assassination of Abdulaziz by cutting his wrists and announced that "he committed suicide".
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] This book of memoir was commonly referred to as a first-hand testimony of the assassination of Abdulaziz.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Yet it was proven, later on, that Abdulhamid II never wrote nor dictated such a document.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdülaziz's family was also convinced that he was murdered, according to the statements of one of his consorts Neşerek Kadın and his daughter Nazime Sultan.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Neşerek herself died just days later, and her brother Hasan, in an act of vengeance, raided a cabinet meeting, killing and injuring several ministers.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Abdulaziz's harem was notorious because, although slavery in the Ottoman Empire had been formally abolished, his mother Pertevniyal Sultan continued to send him slave girls from the Caucasus via the Circassian slave trade.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] In addition to these, Abdülaziz planned to marry the Egyptian princess Tawhida Hanim, daughter of the Egyptian Khedive Isma'il Pasha.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] His Grand Vizier, Mehmed Fuad Pasha, was opposed to marriage and wrote a note for the sultan explaining that marriage would be politically counterproductive and would give Egypt an undue advantage.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] However, the Grand Chamberlain, instead of handing the note to the sultan, read it to him in public, humiliating him.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/abdülaziz-of-the-ottoman-empire] Although the marriage project was abandoned, Fuad was fired for the accident.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/aberdonia-yacht] She was completely restored in the late 1980s, including fitting two new Perkins Diesel engines.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:hms-warrior-1860/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Her current rescue boat/ pushboat is an Achilles hypalon inflatable named W’ha-lé, equipped with an 20hp Yamaha outboard named Porpoise.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] W’ha-lé was stolen from Adventuress in her first months of service in 2022 but was quickly recovered.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] In her starboard davits Adventuress carries a 1979 Sid Skiff built by Ray Speck in Sausalito.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] A-ya’-she was the 2023 Port Townsend Wooden Boat Festival Short Course-Fixed Seat Rowing race champion.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Her name means “Little One” in Chippewa/Ojibwe.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] The boat also participated in the 2024 Port Townsend Wooden Boat Festival “Row Row Row My Boat” event.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Adventuress’ former rescue boats were named Hobbes (outboard: Calvin) and Jefé (outboard: Fast Eddie).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Around 1952, *Adventuress* was brought to Seattle where she went through several owners.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Through his non-profit, Youth Adventure, Inc, Monty Morton and Co-Captain Karl Mehrer began a sail training program for teen girls and boys.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] During this period Captain Mehrer, his son Tim Mehrer, and a crew of volunteers began a complete renovation including the installation of four watertight bulkheads that led to the ship’s 1975 Coast Guard Certification.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] In 1974 Ernestine Bennett became President of the Youth Adventure, Inc.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Ernestine Bennett and Captain Mehrer continued the sail training program for an additional 15 years.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] In 1988, Sound Experience began conducting educational programs on the vessel, and the following year she was listed as a National Historic Landmark.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Today *Adventuress* is operated by the non-profit organization Sound Experience, as a platform for environmental education about Puget Sound.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] She sails from March into October, on trips ranging from 3 hours to 7 days.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/adventuress-schooner] Paid employees and volunteers perform office, crew, and maintenance work.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] The ship was originally built for the Argentine Naval Academy.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] ARA *Presidente Sarmiento* made thirty seven annual training cruises including six circumnavigations of the globe.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] The ship was retired as a seagoing vessel in 1938, but continued to serve without sails on Argentine rivers around 1950 and as a stationary training ship until 1961.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] It is now maintained in its original 1898 appearance as a museum ship in Puerto Madero near downtown Buenos Aires.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] In addition to its sailing rig this ship includes a large triple expansion steam engine supplied by two coal-fired boilers exhausting through the rear stack.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] An additional auxiliary boiler exhausting through the forward stack provides steam for other than propulsion, including two engines driving electrical generators on the main deck (below the weather deck).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] A three-wheel chain drive allows up to six helmsmen to control the rudder.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] Such a crew of operators was not always required due to the inclusion of an electric servo-drive for normal operation but was useful for the training of cadets.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] Four Armstrong gun mounts are positioned amidships, two on each side, with additional smaller weapons.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] The museum information indicates those as 5-inch pieces, but Norman Friedman identifies those as 120-mm L45 Elswick Pattern Y.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] Documentation on the ship shows these having had some armor, but the present installations are bare.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] A single torpedo scuttle using gravity expulsion exited at the bow.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] The scuttle has been removed and the exit port welded shut, but in the current museum configuration a torpedo is suspended in a position on the main deck ready to enter the former scuttle entrance.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] Additional torpedo storage is provided below this main deck.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-presidente-sarmiento] It is moored in Puerto Madero close to the Bicentennial Plaza and is now the **ARA *Presidente Sarmiento* Frigate Museum**.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The corvette **ARA *Uruguay***, is a floating museum ship, berthed at Puerto Madero in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] It was built in England and commissioned into the Argentine navy in 1874: it was decommissioned in 1926.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The last of the legendary squadron of President Sarmiento, the *Uruguay* took part in revolutions, expeditions, rescues, and was even floating headquarters of the Navy School.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] During its operational history 1874–1926 the *Uruguay* has served as a gunboat, school ship, expedition support ship, Antarctic rescue ship, fisheries base supply ship, and hydrographic survey vessel, and is now a museum ship in Buenos Aires.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The ship was built in 1874 at Laird Bros.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] (now Cammell Laird) shipyard of Birkenhead, England, at a cost of £32,000.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] This ship is rigged to a barque sailplan (three masts, two of which have cross spars).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The ship's steel hull is sheathed in teak.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The ship's namesake is an earlier Argentine Navy schooner, a seven-gun combatant in the Battle of Juncal, 1827.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The vessel was built in 1874 at the Laird Brothers shipyard in Birkenhead, United Kingdom, as part of an early programme to modernise the Argentine Navy.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Designed as a small but robust gunboat, she combined a steel-reinforced hull with a barque rig, reflecting the transitional naval technology of the period in which steam propulsion was supplemented by sail for extended range and endurance.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Following completion, the ship was delivered to Argentina later that year and commissioned into naval service.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Initially employed as a gunboat, the vessel was soon reassigned to training duties as part of the Navy’s early efforts to formalise officer instruction and seamanship training.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1878, the ship took part in Commodore Louis Pye’s expedition to Patagonia, south of the Santa Cruz River, alongside the monitor *Los Andes* and the gunboat *Constitución*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The mission formed part of Argentina’s efforts to assert sovereignty over sparsely controlled southern territories during a period of regional tension with Chile.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Following internal disruption within the emerging Argentine Naval Academy,associated with the so-called “Mutiny of the Overcoats” (*el Motín de los Gabanes*) in Zárate—the vessel was repurposed as a floating headquarters for naval instruction and administration.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1879, while stationed in Buenos Aires, she hosted the graduation of the Academy’s first class of naval officers.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1884, the vessel supported international scientific commissions deployed to the Argentine coast to observe the Transit of Venus.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] She served as a transport and logistical platform for astronomical observations conducted in remote coastal regions.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1887, the ship was withdrawn from training service and extensively rebuilt for long-range expeditionary operations.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The refit significantly altered her capabilities: the hull was reinforced, watertight bulkheads were installed dividing the vessel into eight compartments, and a new vertical engine—sourced from the wrecked destroyer *Santa Fe*—replaced the original propulsion system.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] These modifications increased internal volume for coal, fuel, and freshwater storage, improving endurance in remote southern waters.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Additional upgrades included heating systems, improved internal communications, removal of bilge keels, and revised sail rigging adapted for harsh southern conditions.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1903, the vessel underwent a further major reconstruction to prepare for Antarctic rescue operations.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The refit strengthened the hull, improved insulation using cork and sawdust, expanded fuel and water capacity, and further adapted rigging for polar navigation.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] A specially selected crew was assembled for operations in extreme conditions.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Between 1901 and 1903, the vessel carried out her most notable mission: the rescue of the stranded Swedish Antarctic Expedition led by Otto Nordenskjöld.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] After the expedition ship *Antarctic* was crushed by ice, the *Uruguay*, under the command of Lieutenant Commander Julián Irízar, was dispatched to locate survivors and succeeded in rescuing all members of the expedition.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Following a return voyage marked by severe storms and partial dismasting, the vessel reached Puerto Santa Cruz, where news of the rescue was transmitted to Buenos Aires.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] On 2 December 1903, she arrived in Buenos Aires to widespread public celebration and official honours.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] The vessel subsequently supported the Third French Antarctic Expedition led by Jean-Baptiste Charcot, providing logistical assistance and transport in Antarctic waters.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] Over the following decades, the ship operated extensively across the Drake Passage, Cape Horn, and sub-Antarctic waters.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] She supplied Argentine bases in the South Orkney Islands and South Georgia, supported the Sociedad Argentina de Pesca whaling station, and conducted hydrographic and cartographic surveys essential for navigation in the South Atlantic.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] After 52 years of service, the vessel was decommissioned in 1926.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] She was subsequently repurposed as a floating ammunition depot at Río Santiago.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1954, the ship was reconstructed at the Río Santiago Shipyard and restored for preservation.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] She was later moored near the Naval School and formally withdrawn from active naval service in 1962.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/ara-uruguay] In 1967, the vessel was declared a National Historic Monument.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She subsequently served as a storeship and depot ship, and in 1904 was assigned to the Royal Navy's torpedo training school.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship was converted into an oil jetty in 1927 and remained in that role until 1979, at which point she was donated by the Navy to The Maritime Trust for restoration.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The restoration process took eight years, during which many of her features and fittings were either restored or recreated.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] When this was finished she returned to Portsmouth as a museum ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Listed as part of the National Historic Fleet, *Warrior* has been based in Portsmouth since 1987.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The launching of the steam-powered ship of the line *Napoléon* by France in 1850 began an arms race between France and Britain that lasted for a decade.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The situation was perceived to be so serious that Queen Victoria asked the Admiralty if the navy was adequate for the tasks that it would have to perform in wartime.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] *Warrior* and her sister were ordered in response.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Admiralty initially specified that the ship should be capable of 15 kn (28 km/h; 17 mph), and have a full set of sails for worldwide cruising range.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Iron construction was chosen as it gave the best trade-off between speed and protection; an iron hull was lighter than a wooden one of the same size and shape, giving more capacity for guns, armour and engines.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Chief Constructor of the Navy Isaac Watts and the Chief Engineer Thomas Lloyd designed the ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] To minimise risk they copied the hull design of the large wooden frigate HMS *Mersey*, modifying it for iron construction and to accommodate an armoured box, or citadel, amidships along the single gun deck, which protected most of the ship's guns.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Ships with this configuration of guns and armour are classified as broadside ironclads.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The *Warrior*-class design used many well-proven technologies that had been used in ocean-going ships for years, including her iron hull, marine steam engine, and screw propeller; only her wrought-iron armour was a major technological advance.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Brown wrote, "What made [*Warrior*] truly novel was the way in which these individual aspects were blended together, making her the biggest and most powerful warship in the world." Faster, better armoured and harder to hit than her rivals, she was superior to any existing naval ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Admiralty stopped construction of all wooden ships of the line, and ordered another 11 ironclads over the next few years.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Although built in response to *Gloire*, the *Warrior* had a very different operational concept from the French ship, which was meant to replace wooden ships of the line.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The *Warriors* were designed by Watts as 40-gun armoured frigates, not intended to stand in the line of battle, as the Admiralty was uncertain about their ability to withstand concentrated fire from wooden two- and three-deck ships of the line.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Unlike *Gloire*, they were planned to be fast enough to force battle on a fleeing enemy and to control to their own advantage the range at which a battle was fought.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In contrast to *Gloire*'s square profile, *Warrior* has a clipper bow, but she is twice as long as a typical clipper ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] HMS *Warrior* is 380 ft 2 in (115.9 m) long between perpendiculars and 420 ft (128.0 m) long overall.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She has a beam of 58 ft 4 in (17.8 m) and a draught of 26 ft 9 in (8.2 m).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship displaces 9,137 long tons (9,284 t) and has a tonnage of 6,109 tons burthen.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship's length made her relatively unmanoeuvrable, making it harder for her to use her strengthened stem for ramming, an ancient tactic that was coming back into use at the time.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ends of the hull are subdivided by watertight transverse bulkheads and decks into 92 compartments, and the hull has a double bottom underneath the engine and boiler rooms.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The armament of the *Warrior*-class ships was originally intended to be 40 68-pounder guns, a smoothbore muzzle-loading design, 19 on each side on the main deck and one each fore and aft as chase guns on the upper deck.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] During construction the armament was changed to include 10 Armstrong 110-pounder guns, an early rifled breech loader (RBL) design, along with 26 68-pounders, and four RBL Armstrong 40-pounder guns with a calibre of 4.75 in (121 mm) and a maximum range of 3,800 yd (3,500 m).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] It had been planned to replace all the 68-pounders with the innovative 110-pounder, whose 7 in (178 mm) shell could reach 4,000 yd (3,700 m), but poor results in armour-penetration tests halted this.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] During the first use in action of a 110-pounder aboard HMS *Euryalus* in 1863, the gun was incorrectly loaded and the vent piece was blown out of the breech when fired.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] They were labour-intensive to load and fire, and were henceforth only used with a reduced propellant charge, which left them ineffective against ironclad ships.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] All the guns could fire either solid shot or explosive shells.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The 68-pounders could also fire molten iron shells, filled with iron melted in a furnace between the two forward boilers.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The 40-pounder Armstrong guns were replaced with a better design of the same calibre in 1863.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] *Warrior*'s original armament was replaced during her 1864–1867 refit with 24 7-inch and four 8 in (203 mm) rifled muzzle-loading (RML) guns.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship also received four RBL Armstrong 20-pounders for use as saluting guns.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The RML 8-inch gun could penetrate 9.6 in (244 mm) of wrought iron armour at the muzzle, and the RML 7-inch gun could pierce 7.7 in (196 mm).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The armour covered the middle 213 ft (64.9 m) of the ship and extended 16 ft (4.9 m) above the waterline and 6 ft (1.8 m) below it.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The guns on the main deck were protected from raking fire by 4.5-inch transverse bulkheads.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ends of the ship were unprotected, but were subdivided into watertight compartments to minimise flooding.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The lack of armour at the stern rendered the steering gear and rudder vulnerable.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship's crew comprised 50 officers and 656 ratings in 1863.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The majority of the crew had to do physically demanding tasks; one such duty was the raising of the heaviest manually hauled anchors in maritime history.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The day-to-day life of her crew differed little from those on the navy's traditional wooden-hulled vessels.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The majority of the crew lived on the single gun deck of the *Warrior*; these crewmen slept in hammocks slung from the sides and deck beams, with up to 18 men between each pair of guns.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The officers berthed in the rear of the ship in small individual cabins; the wardroom was also the officers' mess.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The captain had two spacious, well-furnished cabins.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] As an experiment during the ship's first commission, all of *Warrior*'s marines were from Royal Marine Artillery; subsequently some marine infantrymen were assigned as was the usual naval practice.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The marines manned the aft section of guns and slung their hammocks between the crew's accommodation and the officers' cabins.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ironclad was ship rigged and had a sail area of 48,400 sq ft (4,497 m2).
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] *Warrior* reached 13 kn (24 km/h; 15 mph) under sail alone, 2 kn (3.7 km/h; 2.3 mph) faster than her sister ship *Black Prince*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She had the largest hoisting propeller ever made; it weighed 26 long tons (26 t), and 600 men could raise it into the ship to reduce drag while under sail.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] To further reduce drag, both her funnels were telescopic and could be lowered.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Under sail and steam together, the ship once reached 17.5 kn (32.4 km/h; 20.1 mph) against the tide while running from Portsmouth to Plymouth.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] This original figurehead was lost in August 1868 when the ship collided with HMS *Royal Oak*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Once again the Hellyers were recommissioned to carve a replacement featuring the traditional warrior figure.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The new figure was placed inside the dockyard main gate at HMNB Portsmouth from 1900 to 1963 when the ship was modified to become part of the Naval Torpedo School.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] However, exposure to the elements meant rot set in, spreading so far that eventually the figurehead was condemned and destroyed.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Finally, a third figurehead – the one that can be seen on the bow of the ship today – was carved by Jack Whitehead and Norman Gaches at Wootton on the Isle of Wight, between 1981 and 1983 for the reconstruction of the ship that was taking place at Hartlepool.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship was initially assigned to the Channel Squadron under the command of Captain Arthur Cochrane.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In March 1863, *Warrior* escorted the royal yacht that brought Princess Alexandra of Denmark to Britain to marry the Prince of Wales.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The princess appreciated the conduct of the ship's crew, and requested Admiral Sir Michael Seymour to convey to the ship that "she was much pleased".
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Cochrane had the message engraved on a brass plate and fitted to the ship's wheel.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Her descendant, Princess Alexandra of Kent, is now patron of the HMS *Warrior* 1860 Trust.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In mid-1863 the Channel Fleet toured British ports for 12 weeks; the ship received 300,000 visitors, including as many as 13,000 a day in port.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] On 19 September, she rescued the survivors of the Mersey Flat *Mary Agnes*, which had sunk in a collision with the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company's ship *Snaefell* at Liverpool, Lancashire.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] From 4 to 28 July 1869, *Warrior*, with *Black Prince* and the wooden paddle frigate HMS *Terrible*, towed a specially built floating drydock, large enough to accommodate ironclads, 2,700 nmi (5,000 km; 3,100 mi) across the Atlantic from Madeira to Bermuda.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Upon her return to England in late August 1869, Boys was relieved by Captain Frederick Stirling.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] After a refit to clean her hull and replace the figurehead lost in the collision, *Warrior* rejoined the Channel Squadron.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] On 2 March 1870, Captain Henry Glyn assumed command of the ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] While returning from a joint cruise with the Mediterranean Fleet, the ship was present when HMS *Captain* was lost during a severe storm on 7 September.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Further cruises followed, including trips to Madeira and Gibraltar.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] *Warrior* narrowly missed colliding with HMS *Agincourt* when she was following her out of Gibraltar and *Agincourt* grounded on Pearl Rock.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The rapid evolution of warship design, for which *Warrior* was partly responsible, meant that she started to become obsolete only ten years after she had been launched.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In 1871 the Royal Navy commissioned its first mastless capital ship, HMS *Devastation*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In the absence of masts, the main armament could move from the broadside and traverse more freely from a higher position.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In the same year, *Warrior* began a refit that lasted until 1875; it added a poop deck and steam capstan, a shorter bowsprit, and replacement boilers.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In April 1875, the ship was recommissioned, and assigned to the First Reserve, where she served as a guardship at Portland.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In this role, she went on annual summer cruises to various ports.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] During the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878, she was mobilised due to concerns that the victorious Russians might be about to attack Constantinople, forcing Great Britain to intervene, but nothing transpired and *Warrior* cruised to Bantry Bay instead.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In April 1881 she was transferred to the Clyde District, where she served as guardship until 31 May 1883.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Two of her masts were discovered to be rotten that month and with no replacements available, the ship was decommissioned and the masts removed.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The mass scrapping of obsolete ships after World War I had caused a downturn in demand for scrap iron by the time the Navy decided to sell off *Warrior* on 2 April 1925.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] There was no commercial interest in scrapping the old ship, and she remained at Portsmouth for another four years.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She was modified into a mooring jetty beginning on 22 October 1927.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] This entailed the removal of all of her equipment and masts other than her boilers and generators, and the installation of two diesel-driven emergency pumps.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The space under the poop was converted into accommodation for a shipkeeper and his family.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The hulk was towed to her new home, Pembroke Dock in Wales, on 13 March 1929 where she served as a floating oil jetty.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] For the next fifty years, the ship lay just offshore from an oil depot at Llanion Cove.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Navy covered the ship's upper deck with a thick layer of concrete during one of her maintenance dockings before World War II.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In the war, she served as a base ship for coastal minesweepers and, on 27 August 1942, was once again renamed as *Oil Fuel Hulk C77* to release her name for use by a light aircraft carrier, HMS *Warrior* (R31), then under construction.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She refuelled 5,000 ships during her service at Llanion Cove.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Restoring *Warrior* was discussed in the early 1960s, but did not develop into a serious project.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In 1967, the Greater London Council proposed to restore the ship as an attraction in London, but *Warrior* was still required in Pembroke by the Royal Navy and the scheme went no further.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In 1968 the Duke of Edinburgh chaired a meeting that discussed preserving and restoring *Warrior* and other historic vessels, and a year later The Maritime Trust was established to save the decrepit ironclad and other historic ships.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Maritime Trust and a major supporter, the Manifold Trust led by the Conservative Member of Parliament (MP) John Smith, maintained an interest in *Warrior*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In 1976 the Royal Navy announced that the Llanion Oil Depot would close in 1978, and the Manifold Trust began to seek funds to restore her.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] With the promise of financial support for restoration, the Royal Navy donated the ship to the trust in 1979.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Ship's Preservation Trust acquired ownership of the ship in 1983; it became the Warrior Preservation Trust in 1985.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In August 1979 *Warrior* began her 800 mi (1,300 km) journey to her temporary home in the Coal Dock at Hartlepool for restoration as a museum ship.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] She arrived on 2 September 1979 and began the £9 million restoration project, largely funded by the Manifold Trust.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Maritime Trust decided to restore *Warrior* to her 1862 condition with the aim that no further major work would be necessary for the next 20 years.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The first two years of the restoration were generally devoted to safely removing material added after her first commission, like the poop deck and the 200 long tons (200 t) of concrete decking.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Intensive research was done to find detailed descriptions of the ship and her equipment as of 1862 to make the restoration as accurate as economically feasible.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Sources included surviving official records, and the papers of those who had served on the ship during her active service.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Bolt-holes and ridges in the paint gave clues to the location of some fittings and fixtures, and the sketch plans of Midshipman Henry Murray, found in Captain Cochrane's Letter Book, showed the locations of the armament, moveable fittings and stores.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Work on carving a replacement for *Warrior*'s figurehead, which was destroyed in the 1960s, began in 1981 using photographs of the original as a guide.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The 12 ft (3.7 m) work-in-progress was displayed at the 1982 London International Boat Show with the carvers, Jack Whitehead and Norman Gaches from the Isle of Wight, still at work; it dominated coverage of the show.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Before it was finished in mid-1983, the figurehead appeared on the BBC children's television programme *Blue Peter*.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] For much of 1984 it was displayed at the Main Gate of the Portsmouth Royal Dockyard.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] It was mounted on the ship on 6 February 1985.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Replacement of the ship's 86-foot-3-inch-tall (26.3 m), 42-inch-wide (1.1 m) lower masts in wood was not feasible, so they were made of steel tube cut and welded to shape, with a ladder inside each mast to allow access to the platforms on the masts.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The three masts and the bowsprit were stepped in place between September 1984 and February 1985.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] *Warrior*'s engines, boilers and auxiliary machinery were considered too expensive to rebuild, so replicas were built from sheet steel with a few components made from cast iron to duplicate the look of the real equipment.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The replica engines can rotate slowly, using electrical power, to allow visitors to imagine how they might have looked in operation.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Woolwich Rotunda Artillery Museum and the States of Jersey lent examples of *Warrior*'s original primary guns, the muzzle-loading 68-pounder and the breech-loading 110-pounder, which were used as moulds for fibreglass replicas.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The Armstrong guns were built with working breeches; they, and the muzzles of all the guns, had to be sealed to prevent people leaving rubbish in them.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] Little information was available on the wooden gun carriages despite extensive research, and a prototype had to be developed and tested before they could be built.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] In 1985 a new berth beside Portsmouth Harbour railway station was dredged, and a new jetty constructed in preparation for *Warrior*'s arrival in Portsmouth.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The ship left Hartlepool on 12 June 1987 under the command of Captain Collin Allen and was towed 390 mi (630 km) to the Solent in four days.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] When she entered Portsmouth Harbour she was welcomed by thousands of people lining the town walls and shore, and by over 90 boats and ships.
[src:hms-warrior-1860/hms-warrior-1860] The restored ironclad was renamed HMS *Warrior* (1860) to avoid confusion with the Northwood Headquarters, commissioned as HMS *Warrior* in 1963, which was at the time the operational headquarters of the Royal Navy.
